#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:22
#, no-c-format
msgid "Achieving &pcidssa; compliance"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:25
#, no-c-format
msgid "To protect customers and the business itself, companies that handle credit card payments must keep data as safe and secure as possible. Following the &pcidss; helps to secure all areas that are connected to payment processes and to implement security-relevant actions to keep the data and the computing environment safe."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:52
#, no-c-format
msgid "This document aims to provide a basic understanding of how &productnamex; can be configured to comply with the &pcidss;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:56
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is important to understand that protecting systems includes more than configuration. The entire environment and people involved must be taken into account."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:61
#, no-c-format
msgid "An essential part of implementing &pcidssa; is the combination of actions:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:66
#, no-c-format
msgid "Create a secure configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:71
#, no-c-format
msgid "Track and review all changes made to the configuration: who changed what at which point in time."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:78
#, no-c-format
msgid "What is the &pcidssa;?"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:79
#, no-c-format
msgid "The &pcidss; (&pcidssa;) is a set of requirements to guide a merchant to protect cardholder data. The standard covers six main categories with currently 12 requirement topics on how to implement, protect, maintain and monitor systems that are involved in credit cardholder data processing."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:86
#, no-c-format
msgid "&pcidssa; was created and is maintained by the PCI Security Standards Council (SSC), which was founded by the five major credit card brands, Visa, MasterCard, American Express, Discover, and JCB. In December 2004, &pcidssa; 1.0 was released to address the growing threat of online credit card fraud. The current version, &pcidssa; version 3.2, has been available since April 2016."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:96
#, no-c-format
msgid "Build and maintain a secure network and systems"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:98
#, no-c-format
msgid "Install and maintain a firewall configuration to protect cardholder data"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:104
#, no-c-format
msgid "Do not use vendor-supplied defaults for system passwords and other security parameters"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:111
#, no-c-format
msgid "Protect cardholder data"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:113
#, no-c-format
msgid "Protect stored cardholder data"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:118
#, no-c-format
msgid "Encrypt transmission of cardholder data across open, public networks"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:124
#, no-c-format
msgid "Maintain a vulnerability management program"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:126
#, no-c-format
msgid "Protect all systems against malware and regularly update anti-virus software or programs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:132
#, no-c-format
msgid "Develop and maintain secure systems and applications"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:138
#, no-c-format
msgid "Implement strong access control measures"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:140
#, no-c-format
msgid "Restrict access to cardholder data by business need to know"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:145
#, no-c-format
msgid "Identify and authenticate access to system components"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:150
#, no-c-format
msgid "Restrict physical access to cardholder data"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:156
#, no-c-format
msgid "Regularly monitor and test networks"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:158
#, no-c-format
msgid "Track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:163
#, no-c-format
msgid "Regularly test security systems and processes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:169
#, no-c-format
msgid "Maintain an information security policy"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:171
#, no-c-format
msgid "Maintain a policy that addresses information security for all personnel"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:176
#, no-c-format
msgid "Most requirements of &pcidssa; are organizational guidelines that help ensure the security of all areas involved with cardholder data. There is usually no specific wording of the technical aspects."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:181
#, no-c-format
msgid "This means that it is up to auditors to decide which security settings are valid for a requirement and which are not. Therefore, the recommendations in this document can only provide a starting point for implementing the &pcidssa; and are necessarily subject to discussion."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:189
#, no-c-format
msgid "Focus of this document: areas relevant to the operating system"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:190
#, no-c-format
msgid "The &pcidssa; covers a wide range of aspects related to cardholder data. Not all of these aspects concern the operating system and this document will not focus on these. Instead, this document focuses on aspects that affect OS configuration, including:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:198
#, no-c-format
msgid "System security"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:203
#, no-c-format
msgid "Access control"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:208
#, no-c-format
msgid "System maintenance to protect against known vulnerabilities"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:213
#, no-c-format
msgid "Topics beyond the scope of this document include data processing applications, database design, and formal processes outside of the OS scope. In particular, requirement 9 (restrict physical access) and requirement 12 (maintain a policy) are not discussed extensively in this document."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:222
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirements in detail"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:223
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following section goes through relevant parts of the &pcidssa; in detail, following the ordering of the standard itself."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:228
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 1: install and maintain a firewall configuration to protect cardholder data"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:229
#, no-c-format
msgid "The listed terms in this section are mostly design, documentation and formal process requirements. All changes to the firewalls and routers need to be approved, documented and verified, and all stakeholders need to be involved. The network design includes a DMZ environment, access to the Internet, a protected network for database servers, traffic filtering rules between network segments, etc."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:237
#, no-c-format
msgid "In addition to a dedicated firewall and router, &productnamex; comes with a host firewall based on iptables. The system can be easily configured to allow only connections on certain inbound ports. With the &yast; firewall module it is also possible to define more complex rules. For example, to disable connections not coming from certain network addresses. This allows integrating the local system firewall into an overall firewall design that maximizes network security."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:246
#, no-c-format
msgid "In generalized terms, the technical points in requirement 1 are the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:252
#, no-c-format
msgid "Identify insecure services and protocols."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:257
#, no-c-format
msgid "Limit traffic to and from the system so that unneeded and unwanted traffic is directly avoided."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:266
#, no-c-format
msgid "1.1.6.b identify insecure services, protocols, and ports allowed; and verify that security features are documented for each service"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:269
#, no-c-format
msgid "This task is embedded in the requirement to identify, document, and justify all services and protocols running on a system. Of special interest are services and protocols that could lead to a security risk. If an insecure service or protocol is used, it must be evaluated to understand its potential security impact. Services or protocols that are not necessary for the business to function should be disabled or removed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:281
#, no-c-format
msgid "1.2.1.b Verify that inbound and outbound traffic is limited to that which is necessary for the cardholder data environment"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:286
#, no-c-format
msgid "Outbound traffic should only be allowed in specifically defined cases. To allow specific traffic, manually add rules for outbound traffic."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:291
#, no-c-format
msgid "Make the SSH daemon only reachable on the administration interface and not on the general network card if possible. Define the source addresses that a service allows traffic from."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:296
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, to allow only outbound DNS requests over the interface <systemitem>eth0</systemitem> to server <systemitem class=\"ipaddress\">10.0.0.1</systemitem> , use:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:301
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;<command>firewall-cmd</command> --permanent --direct --add-rule ipv4 filter OUTPUT 23 \\\n"
      "    -d 10.0.0.1/32 -o eth0 -p udp -m udp --dport 53 -j ACCEPT\n"
      "&prompt.root;<command>firewall-cmd</command> --reload"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:304
#, no-c-format
msgid "To block all other outbound traffic, see <xref linkend=\"vle-pcidss-deny-all\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:310
#, no-c-format
msgid "1.2.1.c Verify that all other inbound and outbound traffic is specifically denied"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:315
#, no-c-format
msgid "Deny all outbound and inbound traffic for which no exceptions are defined as stated in the previous section. Forwarding is usually completely disabled by a kernel parameter and should not be enabled for endpoint servers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:321
#, no-c-format
msgid "&firewalld; in &productname; by default blocks all inbound traffic."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:325
#, no-c-format
msgid "To block all outbound traffic, manually add the following rules:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:328
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;<command>firewall-cmd</command> --permanent --direct --add-rule ipv4 filter OUTPUT 0 -m conntrack --ctstate RELATED,ESTABLISHED -j ACCEPT\n"
      "&prompt.root;<command>firewall-cmd</command> --permanent --direct --add-rule ipv6 filter OUTPUT 0 -m conntrack --ctstate RELATED,ESTABLISHED -j ACCEPT\n"
      "&prompt.root;<command>firewall-cmd</command> --permanent --direct --add-rule ipv4 filter OUTPUT 99 -j DROP\n"
      "&prompt.root;<command>firewall-cmd</command> --permanent --direct --add-rule ipv6 filter OUTPUT 99 -j DROP\n"
      "&prompt.root;<command>firewall-cmd</command> --reload"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:333
#, no-c-format
msgid "In addition, inbound traffic can also be configured for certain services via the TCP wrapper configuration file <filename>/etc/hosts.deny</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:338
#, no-c-format
msgid "Most of the following tasks are about examining and verifying that the defined inbound and outbound rules are really limiting the traffic between and within all network segments, like the DMZ and the Internet, to a necessary minimum for full system operation."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:347
#, no-c-format
msgid "1.3.3 Implement anti-spoofing measures to detect and block forged source IP addresses from entering the network"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:352
#, no-c-format
msgid "There are two ways to implement anti-spoofing measurements in &productnamex;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:359
#, no-c-format
msgid "<systemitem>iptables</systemitem> rules that only allow input from certain addresses on specified interfaces"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:360
#, no-c-format
msgid "The used address space for communications can be clearly defined in the system setup. Any use of addresses that violates these definitions can be logged and trigger an alarm."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:370
#, no-c-format
msgid "Linux kernel reverse path filtering"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:371
#, no-c-format
msgid "This feature discards packet replies that do not go through the same interface as the initial packet. This feature is enabled by default in &productnamex; and can be checked with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:378
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;cat /proc/sys/net/ipv4/conf/all/rp_filter"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:379
#, no-c-format
msgid "When enabled, this returns <literal>1</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:388
#, no-c-format
msgid "1.3.5 Permit only <quote>established</quote> connections into the network"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:393
#, no-c-format
msgid "&firewalld; enables connection tracking via <literal>iptables</literal> . Connections to an interface that has been marked as external are dropped by default. Only connections that are associated with an established connection are allowed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:399
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is possible to define certain services that are allowed to connect to an external interface. However, this must be in compliance with the general security policy."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:404
#, no-c-format
msgid "Keep in mind that the first line of defense against malicious connections from the Internet should be a dedicated firewall system that handles all traffic and acts as a gatekeeper. Unwanted connections should never reach the DMZ network. However, simple firewall rules on &productnamex; systems can help avoid misconfigurations and act as another line of defense."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:415
#, no-c-format
msgid "1.3.7 Do not disclose private IP addresses and routing information to unauthorized parties"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:420
#, no-c-format
msgid "A &productnamex; system can also act as a router to forward traffic from one interface to another network on a second interface. It is possible to use Network Address Translation (NAT) on the external interface so that no internal IP address is actually exposed to the outside. This is done to mitigate the information an external attacker can gather by simply analyzing the network traffic. NAT can also be used on virtualization hosts or container-based environments that connect to the outside via a specific interface."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:435
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 2: do not use vendor-supplied defaults for system passwords and other security parameters"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:436
#, no-c-format
msgid "During the installation of &productnamex;, general system passwords are already set by the administrator. The setup also uses a password checker ( <command>cracklib</command> ) that identifies weak entries against a dictionary. This means that the standard configuration already includes customer-defined security options for most services."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:443
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information about OS security, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"book-security\"/>.</phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Security Guide</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:450
#, no-c-format
msgid "2.1 Always change vendor-supplied defaults and remove or disable unnecessary default accounts before installing a system on the network."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:455
#, no-c-format
msgid "The configuration of any system service must be evaluated to meet the needed security standards. This goes from limiting the used protocols to only allow currently secure versions and to disable legacy implementations, to the definition of access controls and authentication. The default settings of &productnamex; already provide good overall security, but they can be tweaked further."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:463
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, the following security settings might be relevant:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:468
#, no-c-format
msgid "By default, the SNMP daemon only allows incoming requests to <systemitem>localhost</systemitem> . However, the default community string is named <literal>public</literal> and should be changed before accepting general inbound connections."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:476
#, no-c-format
msgid "By default, certain insecure upstream settings of the <systemitem class=\"daemon\">sshd</systemitem> daemon are listed and commented out inside the <systemitem class=\"daemon\">sshd</systemitem> configuration file <filename>/etc/ssh/sshd_config</filename> . For example, the insecure protocol version 1 and empty passwords ( <literal>PermitEmptyPasswords no</literal> ) are already disabled."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:484
#, no-c-format
msgid "To further increase SSH security, if applicable, deny direct <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> access by setting <literal>PermitRootLogin</literal> to <literal>no</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:491
#, no-c-format
msgid "Default settings can be customized by automating system installation with an &ay; profile. This allows rolling out new instances of &productnamex; and automatically enabling an evaluated configuration. This setup procedure can also be automated with the &susemgr;. For more information, see the &susemgr; documentation at <link xlink:href=\"https://documentation.suse.com/suma/\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:499
#, no-c-format
msgid "By default, &productnamex; does not create additional accounts apart from the <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> administrative user. There are system accounts defined in <filename>/etc/passwd</filename> , but they are not activated and therefore not directly reachable. This can be validated by checking the lines inside the <filename>/etc/shadow</filename> file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:507
#, no-c-format
msgid "In that file, the second column represents the defined password:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:512
#, no-c-format
msgid "An asterisk ( <literal>*</literal> ) means that a password was never defined and the account is therefore locked."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:518
#, no-c-format
msgid "An exclamation mark ( <literal>!</literal> ) stands for a locked account and can appear either alone or in front of a password hash."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:527
#, no-c-format
msgid "2.2 Develop configuration standards for all system components. Ensure that these standards address all known security vulnerabilities and are consistent with industry-accepted system hardening standards."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:533
#, no-c-format
msgid "As mentioned in the &pcidssa; document, possible sources for industry-accepted hardening standards are:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:539
#, no-c-format
msgid "Center for Internet Security (CIS)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:542
#, no-c-format
msgid "International Organization for Standardization (ISO)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:545
#, no-c-format
msgid "SysAdmin Audit Network Security (SANS) Institute"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:548
#, no-c-format
msgid "National Institute of Standards Technology (NIST)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:551
#, no-c-format
msgid "As the &pcidssa; requirements are not specified precisely, there is no direct relationship between hardening standards and specific requirements. However, other hardening resources can also help in complying with these specifications, including <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"book-security\"/></phrase> . <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Security Guide</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:562
#, no-c-format
msgid "2.2.1 Implement only one primary function per server to prevent functions that require different security levels from co-existing on the same server. (For example, web servers, database servers, and DNS should be implemented on separate servers.)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:569
#, no-c-format
msgid "To help separate services, use the variety of virtualization and containerization methods included with &productnamex;: &kvm;, &xen;, &lxc;, and &docker;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:574
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can also run &productnamex; on third-party virtualization servers like &esx; or &hyperv; to achieve service separation."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:578
#, no-c-format
msgid "When using the options built in to &productnamex;, see:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:583
#, no-c-format
msgid "For information about virtualization, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"book-virt\"/></phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Virtualization Guide</citetitle></phrase> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:591
#, no-c-format
msgid "For information about containerization, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"book-container\"/></phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; &deng; Guide</citetitle></phrase> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:602
#, no-c-format
msgid "2.2.2 Enable only necessary services, protocols, daemons, etc., as required for the function of the system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:607
#, no-c-format
msgid "This is directly related to an item of requirement 1: To allow only services that are really needed and are using secure protocols and settings ( <xref linkend=\"vle-pcidss-insecure-service\"/> ). All parties involved must be aware of the dangers of using insecure communication. Research, clearly document, and communicate the risk of using insecure protocols and services."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:615
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enable and disable system services using the following <command>systemctl</command> commands:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:621
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;systemctl status <replaceable>SERVICE</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:624
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;systemctl enable <replaceable>SERVICE</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:627
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;systemctl disable <replaceable>SERVICE</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:630
#, no-c-format
msgid "To list all available services that are installed on the system and see their status, use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:634
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;systemctl list-unit-files --type=service"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:638
#, no-c-format
msgid "2.2.3.a Inspect configuration settings to verify that security features are documented and implemented for all insecure services, daemons, or protocols."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:644
#, no-c-format
msgid "To add an additional layer of security to insecure services, use VPN tunnels (for example, IPsec). With a VPN tunnel, network traffic of such services can be isolated and all data is protected against eavesdropping, both internally and externally. However, note that the communication is still insecure at the endpoints of the VPN tunnel and that this is only a workaround."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:652
#, no-c-format
msgid "For additional security within &productnamex;, use &selnx; or &aa;. However, the setup of these frameworks is beyond the scope of this document:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:678
#, no-c-format
msgid "2.2.5.a Select a sample of system components and inspect the configurations to verify that all unnecessary functionality (for example, scripts, drivers, features, subsystems, file systems, etc.) is removed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:685
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Linux kernel is the main system component. It consists of a core image that is extended by kernel modules which are loaded depending on the hardware and system design. For example: Network card drivers are automatically loaded depending on the system’s network card. File system modules can be enabled to extend the Linux kernel’s file system support."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:693
#, no-c-format
msgid "The list of loaded kernel modules is usually quite long and includes modules that are only used occasionally. The kernel module framework allows blacklisting modules and limiting which functionalities are loaded."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:699
#, no-c-format
msgid "To block modules from being loaded, configure them via the directory <filename>/etc/modprobe.d</filename> . For example, the kernel module <literal>floppy</literal> is only necessary for systems that have a floppy drive. On systems that do not have a floppy drive, prevent the module from loading: Create a configuration file <filename>/etc/modprobe.d/00-disable-modules.conf</filename> with the following content:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:708
#, no-c-format
msgid "install floppy /bin/true"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:709
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>floppy</literal> module is usually loaded during the execution of the initial RAM disk. Therefore, propagate this configuration change to the <filename>initrd</filename> file using the <command>mkinitrd</command> script."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:715
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;mkinitrd"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:716
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is harder to remove or restrict application functionality, as functionality is in most cases compiled into the application or library itself. Even cases where deleting a file cleanly removes a functionality are problematic: If the file was installed from an RPM package, it will be reinstalled when the package is updated."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:726
#, no-c-format
msgid "2.3 Encrypt all non-console administrative access using strong cryptography. Use technologies such as SSH, VPN, or TLS for web-based management and other non-console administrative access."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:732
#, no-c-format
msgid "Encrypt all administrative network access: SSH with appropriate configuration settings that fit into the security concept should be the tool of choice."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:737
#, no-c-format
msgid "Administrative access can also be granted via a Web site. In this case, the complete connection chain between the browser and the server system must be encrypted. This is done via TLS and X.509 certificates."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:748
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 3: protect stored cardholder data"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:749
#, no-c-format
msgid "This section explains how to handle cardholder and authentication data securely. The following definitions apply:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:755
#, no-c-format
msgid "<emphasis>Cardholder data</emphasis> includes information such as the cardholder name and the Primary Account Number (PAN)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:761
#, no-c-format
msgid "<emphasis>Authentication data</emphasis> includes the Personal Identification Number (PIN) and the Card Validation Code (CVC2)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:767
#, no-c-format
msgid "The main difference between cardholder data and authentication data is that storing authentication is never allowed. In contrast, data such as the PAN can be stored, but must be encrypted and unreadable in case an attacker gains access to the stored data."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:773
#, no-c-format
msgid "The database design for storing cardholder data is beyond the scope of this document. However, data can be encrypted in different ways:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:779
#, no-c-format
msgid "The DBMS can use column-level encryption inside the database scheme."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:785
#, no-c-format
msgid "Alternatively, the database files can be encrypted."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:790
#, no-c-format
msgid "&productnamex; supports full-disk encryption, so that the whole database storage is always encrypted. However, access to an encrypted disk works the same way as to a non-encrypted disk. This is discussed in more detail in requirement 3.4.1."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:800
#, no-c-format
msgid "3.4.1.a If disk encryption is used, inspect the configuration and observe the authentication process to verify that logical access to encrypted file systems is implemented via a mechanism that is separate from the native operating system’s authentication mechanism (for example, not using local user account databases or general network login credentials)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:809
#, no-c-format
msgid "The guidance description of the &pcidssa; document says the following about this requirement: <quote>Full disk encryption helps to protect data in the event of physical loss of a disk and therefore may be appropriate for portable devices that store cardholder data.</quote>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:815
#, no-c-format
msgid "From an administrator’s point of view, a block device encryption with the Linux Unified Key Setup (LUKS)/dm-crypt offers an abstraction layer that allows the usage of encrypted disks in the same way as unencrypted disks."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:821
#, no-c-format
msgid "Therefore, access control can only be limited with the general ACL permissions that the file system offers. To comply with this requirement, the decryption key used must not be associated with any general login credentials or authentication methods."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:828
#, no-c-format
msgid "When using LUKS, this is usually fulfilled: The password needs to be entered separately when booting, inserting portable devices or manually mounting disks."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:833
#, no-c-format
msgid "LUKS is fully integrated into &productnamex; and can be used via &yast; to create new partitions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:840
#, no-c-format
msgid "3.4.1.c Examine the configurations and observe the processes to verify that cardholder data on removable media is encrypted wherever stored."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:845
#, no-c-format
msgid "As described in <xref linkend=\"vle-pcidss-encrypt-disk\"/> , LUKS/dm-crypt provides full-disk encryption that fulfills this requirement. Access to the stored data is only possible via a decryption password that must be entered when the disk is mounted."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:856
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 4: encrypt transmission of cardholder data across open, public networks"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:857
#, no-c-format
msgid "Cardholder data must be encrypted during transmissions over insecure networks. Ideally, encrypt all traffic, externally and internally. This makes it hard for attackers to gain inside information and privileged access to the cardholder data environment."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:865
#, no-c-format
msgid "4.1 Use strong cryptography and security protocols (for example, TLS, IPSEC, SSH, etc.) to safeguard sensitive cardholder data during transmission over open, public networks, including the following: (1) Only trusted keys and certificates are accepted, (2) The protocol in use only supports secure versions or configurations, (3) The encryption strength is appropriate for the encryption methodology in use."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:875
#, no-c-format
msgid "Any connection that transmits sensitive information must be protected against eavesdropping and tampering."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:879
#, no-c-format
msgid "For incoming client requests, use the HTTPS protocol with a secure TLS connection. The authentication is done with a public X.509 certificate that proves to a certain level that the server is the right endpoint the customer is looking for."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:885
#, no-c-format
msgid "&productnamex; comes with a set of services and tools that allow protected HTTPS connections. For example, this can be done directly with the Apache HTTP Server or via <command>stunnel</command> , which functions as a proxy to offer TLS encryption functionality."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:891
#, no-c-format
msgid "IPsec or other VPN technologies can be used for securing the connection between network segments that are connected via a public network. Such connections can also be secured with a public X.509 certificate. For internal usage, it is possible to use a private Certificate Authority (CA) to sign X.509 certificates and to keep track of trusted keys."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:899
#, no-c-format
msgid "In &productnamex;, this can be established directly with <phrase role=\"productname\">strongSwan</phrase> , which is a IPsec-based VPN solution, or with OpenVPN, which uses a custom security protocol."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:904
#, no-c-format
msgid "To administrate the OS, use SSH. For information about configuring SSH to provide better security, see <xref linkend=\"sec-pcidss-requirement-1\"/> and <xref linkend=\"sec-pcidss-requirement-2\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:915
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 5: protect all systems against malware and regularly update anti-virus software or programs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:916
#, no-c-format
msgid "For &pcidssa; compliance, it is necessary to protect against malicious software. Third-party anti-virus software is available from the major anti-virus software vendors and can be integrated into the Linux environment. &productnamex; comes with the open source anti-virus engine &clamav;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:923
#, no-c-format
msgid "&clamav; has a limited set of scanning capabilities and limited performance compared to third-party products. Hence, expect &clamav; to only provide basic protection."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:928
#, no-c-format
msgid "On the other hand, &clamav; is shipped with &productnamex; and it can be included during server installation. This makes it easy to fulfill this requirement, but the drawbacks compared to third-party products need to be clearly understood."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:936
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 6: develop and maintain secure systems and applications"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:937
#, no-c-format
msgid "The major part of this requirement concerns in-house software development, documentation, and design questions that are beyond the scope of this document. However, &productnamex; provides tools that help keep your systems safe:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:945
#, no-c-format
msgid "The software package manager Zypper is a powerful instrument of &productnamex;. Among other things, it resolves dependencies of packages, products, patterns, and patches, has a locking mechanism to prevent package installation, and provides a complete update stack to keep the system up-to-date and protected against known security issues."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:952
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>zypper</command> is part of any &productnamex; installation and has direct access to the update repositories after system registration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:956
#, no-c-format
msgid "For information about Zypper, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"sec-zypper\"/>.</phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Administration Guide, Chapter Managing Software with Command Line Tools, Section Using Zypper</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:965
#, no-c-format
msgid "For system management, &suse; provides &susemgr;, which provides an efficient way to keep systems up-to-date. It offers seamless management of both &productnamex; and &rhel; client systems. This is particularly useful in larger system environments, when you need to check the current update status of each system and to react to known security risks."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:973
#, no-c-format
msgid "For information about &susemgr;, see the <link xlink:href=\"https://documentation.suse.com/suma/\">&susemgr; documentation page</link> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:982
#, no-c-format
msgid "6.2.a Examine policies and procedures related to security patch installation to verify processes are defined for: (1) Installation of applicable critical vendor-supplied security patches within one month of release, (2) Installation of all applicable vendor-supplied security patches within an appropriate time frame (for example, within three months)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:991
#, no-c-format
msgid "To identify patches that need to be installed to secure your system, do the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:995
#, no-c-format
msgid "First, refresh all software repositories, so you have up-to-date information:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:998
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;zypper refresh"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:999
#, no-c-format
msgid "Then use the patch-related commands of Zypper:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1004
#, no-c-format
msgid "Search for important security fixes that have not yet been installed:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:1008
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;zypper list-patches --category security --severity important"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1011
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is also possible to search for CVE or SUSE Bugzilla numbers. By default, only necessary patches are listed by this command. To also show patches that have already been installed, use the parameter <option>--all</option> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:1017
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;zypper list-patches --all --cve=CVE-2016-4957"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1020
#, no-c-format
msgid "To list details of individual patches, use the <command>patch-info</command> subcommand:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:1024
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;zypper patch-info SUSE-SLE-SERVER-12-SP1-2016-600"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1027
#, no-c-format
msgid "To install only important security patches, use the <command>patch</command> subcommand:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:1031
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;zypper patch --category security --severity important"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1034
#, no-c-format
msgid "To perform updates automatically, the parameter <option>--non-interactive</option> , which is supported by all Zypper subcommands, is helpful."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1039
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information about Zypper, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"sec-zypper\"/>.</phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Administration Guide, Chapter Managing Software with Command Line Tools, Section Using Zypper</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:1051
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 7: restrict access to cardholder data by business need to know"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1052
#, no-c-format
msgid "OS access control is a complex topic. Again, this &pcidssa; requirement is not specified precisely and does not specifically state to what degree the restrictions need to be implemented. &productnamex; comes with all general Linux tools to limit and restrict access to certain system areas and components:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1061
#, no-c-format
msgid "Access can be controlled via specific users and groups of users by using the traditional Unix permission settings."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1065
#, no-c-format
msgid "For information about managing permissions, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"cha-security-acls\"/>.</phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Security Guide, Chapter Access Control Lists in Linux</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1073
#, no-c-format
msgid "A more flexible mechanism for file systems are Access Control Lists (ACLs), which offer a more granular approach. &selnx; can be used for maximum system separation and to prevent processes from gaining more resources and access than allowed. &selnx; and &aa; are beyond the scope of this document but should be employed to protect critical systems that are likely to be targeted."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1083
#, no-c-format
msgid "For information about &selnx;, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"cha-selinux\"/>.</phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Security Guide, Chapter Configuring &selnx;</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1091
#, no-c-format
msgid "For information about &aa;, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"part-apparmor\"/>.</phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Security Guide, Part Confining Privileges with &aa;</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:1103
#, no-c-format
msgid "7.1.2 Restrict access to privileged user IDs to least privileges necessary to perform job responsibilities."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1108
#, no-c-format
msgid "The standard Unix permissions allow setting Read, Write, and Execution flags for user and group IDs. A general group called <systemitem class=\"groupname\">others</systemitem> or <systemitem class=\"groupname\">world</systemitem> defines the access for users that do not fit into the first two groups. This provides a straightforward way to grant or deny access to file system resources."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1116
#, no-c-format
msgid "ACLs provide an extra level of restrictions. It is possible to set read-write access for one user ID and only read access for a second one. The same goes for group IDs."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1121
#, no-c-format
msgid "The commands <command>getfacl</command> and <command>setfacl</command> (on &productnamex; shipped with the package <package>acl</package> ) allow direct modification of file system resources. For example, to check and set ACL restrictions of the file <filename>/tmp/test.txt</filename> for the user &exampleuserII;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:1128
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "&prompt.user;<command>getfacl /tmp/test.txt</command>\n"
      "# file: /tmp/test.txt\n"
      "# owner: &exampleuser_plain;\n"
      "# group: users\n"
      "user::r--\n"
      "group::r--\n"
      "other::r--\n"
      "\n"
      "&prompt.user;<command>setfacl -m \"u:&exampleuserII_plain;:rw\" /tmp/test.txt</command>\n"
      "\n"
      "&prompt.user;<command>getfacl /tmp/test.txt</command>\n"
      "# file: /tmp/test.txt\n"
      "# owner: &exampleuser_plain;\n"
      "# group: users\n"
      "user::rw-\n"
      "user:&exampleuserII_plain;:r--\n"
      "group::r--\n"
      "mask::r--\n"
      "other::r--\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1149
#, no-c-format
msgid "Standard Unix permissions include the so-called Sticky Bit. This allows the execution of certain programs with higher privileges than the user who is executing those programs. The best example of this is the <command>passwd</command> tool, which needs to modify <filename>/etc/shadow</filename> to change the user password."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1156
#, no-c-format
msgid "For a more gradual approach to explicitly allowing certain operations or behaviors to binaries, use extended capabilities. As an example of a command that uses extended capabilities by default, consider <command>ping</command> (from the package <package>iputils</package> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1162
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>ping</command> sends ICMP IP packets over the network card. To do so, it needs the <literal>CAP_NET_RAW</literal> capability to be Effective and Permitted ( <literal>+ep</literal> ):"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: security_pcidss.xml:1168
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "&prompt.root;<command>sudo getcap /usr/bin/ping</command>\n"
      "/usr/bin/ping = cap_net_raw+ep\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1172
#, no-c-format
msgid "Login access control to the system can be managed using Pluggable Authentication Modules (PAM). There are several modules available in &productnamex; that allow setups such as logging the login time, multiple authentication mechanisms, and central databases like NIS, LDAP, or &ad;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1179
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information about managing permissions, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"cha-security-acls\"/>.</phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Security Guide, Chapter Access Control Lists in Linux</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:1190
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 8: identify and authenticate access to system components"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1191
#, no-c-format
msgid "Ideally, use a central database with user information and a unique identifier (UID) to grant or deny access to certain system components. This makes it easy to give administrators special access to a group of servers or a database engineer permission for a certain DBMS system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1197
#, no-c-format
msgid "On a stand-alone server, unique identifiers are managed via the standard Linux user and group IDs. These are listed in <filename>/etc/passwd</filename> and <filename>/etc/group</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:1204
#, no-c-format
msgid "8.1.4 Remove/disable inactive user accounts within 90 days."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1208
#, no-c-format
msgid "In this context, there are many advantages to using a centralized infrastructure for user accounts like NIS, LDAP, or &ad;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1214
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is easy to identify and automatically disable inactive accounts."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1219
#, no-c-format
msgid "User accounts only need to be disabled in one place. After their access is revoked, the user cannot use any service that relies on the centralized account infrastructure."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1226
#, no-c-format
msgid "However, if you are using local accounts, these can be checked for inactivity when a user is logging in. This module checks the last login time recorded in <filename>/var/log/lastlog</filename> and calculates the number of days since. By default, access is denied when the inactivity reaches 90 days."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1233
#, no-c-format
msgid "To list the local account's last login time use the command <command>lastlog</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:1240
#, no-c-format
msgid "8.1.6 Limit repeated access attempts by locking out the user ID after not more than six attempts."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1245
#, no-c-format
msgid "As stated in <xref linkend=\"vle-pcidss-disable-user\"/> , a centralized account infrastructure will have this capability. On &productnamex; systems, access attempts can be checked and limited with the <systemitem>pam_tally2</systemitem> PAM module. The module is executed during login time and checks the recorded failed attempts since the last successful login. To check and reset the account status, use the tool <command>pam_tally2</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:1257
#, no-c-format
msgid "8.1.7 Set the lockout duration to a minimum of 30 minutes or until an administrator enables the user ID."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1262
#, no-c-format
msgid "The PAM module <systemitem>pam_tally2</systemitem> described in <xref linkend=\"vle-pcidss-lock-user\"/> can be used to lock an account for a given time after a failed login attempt. The parameter <literal>unlock_time=1800</literal> must be specified in the PAM configuration. By default, only the administrator can reactivate a locked account."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:1273
#, no-c-format
msgid "8.3.1 Incorporate multi-factor authentication for all non-console access into the CDE for personnel with administrative access."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1278
#, no-c-format
msgid "To authenticate users for administrative access with multiple factors, use the following methods:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1284
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use Pluggable Authentication Modules (PAM): This increases flexibility when adding new methods to the authentication process and when adjusting it."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1289
#, no-c-format
msgid "For third-party one-time password (OTP) products, there is usually also a Linux PAM module available."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1293
#, no-c-format
msgid "For information about PAM, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"cha-pam\"/>.</phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Security Guide, Chapter Authentication with PAM</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1301
#, no-c-format
msgid "To add multi-factor authentication for SSH connections, mandate use of public keys in addition to passwords."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1305
#, no-c-format
msgid "To connect to a system, it is then necessary to prove possession of an appropriate private key. At the second stage, you then enter a password. This means attackers need to acquire a private key before they can even try to brute-force a password prompt."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: security_pcidss.xml:1316
#, no-c-format
msgid "8.3.2 Incorporate multi-factor authentication for all remote network access (both user and administrator, and including third-party access for support or maintenance) originating from outside the entity’s network."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1323
#, no-c-format
msgid "For details, see <xref linkend=\"vle-pcidss-multi-factor-local\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:1331
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 9: restrict physical access to cardholder data"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1332
#, no-c-format
msgid "Physical access to systems that are involved in processing cardholder data are not within the scope of general operating system security. Appropriate facility entry controls must be in place to allow on-site personnel and visitors to access systems directly."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:1340
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 10: track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1341
#, no-c-format
msgid "To track user activities, it is important to have a synchronized time reference. This is done via the NTP protocol, which allows servers to keep their local time in synchronization with a central system. The central NTP server inside the cardholder data environment (CDE) should not rely on external connections to the Internet to update the system time. Alternatively, system time can be updated using DCF77 radio transmissions or a GPS receiver."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1351
#, no-c-format
msgid "A synchronized time reference makes it easier to correlate events inside recorded log files. This reference can include general system log entries collected by a central system log server or kernel audit messages by the daemon <systemitem class=\"daemon\">audit</systemitem> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1357
#, no-c-format
msgid "For information about auditing, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"part-audit\"/>.</phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex;, Security Guide, Part &auditguide;</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1363
#, no-c-format
msgid "All auditing requirements from this section can be fulfilled by defining centrally stored auditing rules."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: security_pcidss.xml:1369
#, no-c-format
msgid "Requirement 11: regularly test security systems and processes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1370
#, no-c-format
msgid "Testing the discussed security mechanisms is also a key requirement for &pcidssa;. Evaluating the configurations and testing logging mechanisms can protect against known security risks and ensure that essential information is available to identify possible security breaches. Testing capabilities should be considered ahead of time, during system design already."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1378
#, no-c-format
msgid "To keep track of system integrity, &productnamex; comes with the Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment (&aide;). &aide; creates a hash value database of all relevant OS files. After initialization, it can be used to verify the integrity of all previously saved files. To employ AIDE, it is best to regularly create database snapshots and save them to a central system on which you can evaluate possible modifications."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: security_pcidss.xml:1386
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information about &aide;, see <phrase os=\"sles;sled;osuse\"><xref linkend=\"cha-aide\"/>.</phrase> <phrase os=\"article\"><citetitle>&productnamex; Security Guide, Chapter Intrusion Detection with &aide;</citetitle>.</phrase>"
msgstr ""

